South Africa’s annual inflation rate fell to a six-month low in July. Consumer price growth slowed to 4% from 4.5% in June, the Pretoria-based Statistics South Africa said Wednesday in an emailed statement. The median estimate of 15 economists in a Bloomberg survey was 4.3%. Key Insights: Inflation has remained at or below the 4.5% midpoint of the central bank’s target band every month since December, the longest such streak in more than eight years.
The Monetary Policy Committee revised its inflation forecast for the year to 4.4% from 4.5% at its July meeting. The panel cut the benchmark interest rate by 25 basis points to 6.5%.
A volatile exchange rate and potential return to economic growth in the second quarter may limit the scope for further easing in 2019.
With consumer spending under pressure, the prices of clothing and footwear and household appliances rose less than 2% from a year before, adding to the lower inflation rate. Read: IMF rumors may be the scare South Africa needs